      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Berkelium is a radioactive, synthetic metal - a transuranic element, i.e. an artificially obtained radioactive element with an atomic number higher than 92. It belongs to the actinide series. It is assumed to be a silvery, reactive element. The most stable berkelium isotope is </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">247</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Bk with a half-life of 7000 years. The element was obtained in 1950 by the American scientists: Glenn T. Seaborg, Stanley G. Thompson and Albert Ghiorso. The name is derived </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">from the name of the city in California where it was discovered. The first berkelium compound was produced in 1962 - berkelium(III) chloride </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> – BkC</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">l</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. The obtained sample weighed 3 · </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">10</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">-9</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">g. Other berkelium compounds obtained are : berkelium(IV) oxide – Bk</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
